##Brassicales

#Brassicaceae
Brassica [Cabbage/Broccoli]
Capsella [Shepherd's purse]
Raphanus [Radish]
Sinapis [Mustard]

#Caricaceae
Carica [Papaya]


##Malvales
#Malvaceae
Tilia [Linden]: heart-shaped leaves, pea-like fruits on bract
Theobroma [Cacao]
Cola
Hibiscus
Durio [Durian]
Gossypium [Cotton]
Adansonia [Baobab]
Alcea [Hollyhock]
#Thymelaeaceae
Daphne



##Sapindales

#Rutaceae
Citrus [Orange/Lemon]
Skimmia: small red drupes in panicle

#Sapindaceae
Acer [Maple]: northern hemisphere, shade tolerant
Aesculus [Horse chestnut]
Litchi [Lychee]
Nephelium [Rambutan]

#Anacardiaceae
Mangifera [Mango]
Toxicodendron [Poison ivy]
Anacardium [Cashew]
Rhus [Sumac]
Pistacia [Pistachio]




#Geraniales: herbs, lobed leaves
=Geraniaceae
Geranium: 5 petals
Pelargonium: 2 upper + 3 lower petals
Erodium: explosive seed dispersal, screw-shaped seed drills itself into ground by changes in humidity

#Myrtales
=Onagraceae
Fuchsia: shrubs, decorative flowers
Epilobium / Chamaenerion: willowherbs, tall plants, small pink flowers
=Lythraceae
Punica: pomegranate, shrub
Lythrum: tall plants, small pink flowers
=Myrtaceae
Eucalyptus: Australia
- regenerate after fire
- bark white or colorful
- bark smooth or shedding
Psidium: guava, America
